Bubble Sort is a simple comparison-based sorting algorithm where adjacent elements are compared and swapped if they are in the wrong order. This process repeats multiple times until the array is sorted. After each pass, the largest element “bubbles up” to the end of the array, which is why it is called Bubble Sort
Time Complexity

Best Case: O(n) (when the array is already sorted, using optimization)

Average Case: O(n²)

Worst Case: O(n²)

Space Complexity

O(1) (in-place sorting)
Example

Array: 5, 1, 4, 2, 8

Pass 1

(5,1) → swap → 1,5,4,2,8

(5,4) → swap → 1,4,5,2,8

(5,2) → swap → 1,4,2,5,8

(5,8) → no swap

Result: 1,4,2,5,8 (8 is in correct position)

Pass 2

(1,4) → no swap

(4,2) → swap → 1,2,4,5,8

(4,5) → no swap

Result: 1,2,4,5,8

Pass 3
Array becomes sorted.

Java Code
class BubbleSort {
    static void bubbleSort(int arr[]) {
        int n = arr.length;

        for(int i = 0; i < n-1; i++) {
            for(int j = 0; j < n-i-1; j++) {
                if(arr[j] > arr[j+1]) {
                    int temp = arr[j];
                    arr[j] = arr[j+1];
                    arr[j+1] = temp;
                }
            }
        }
    }
}

Bubble Sort is a sorting algorithm that repeatedly compares adjacent elements and swaps them if they are in the wrong order, causing the largest element to bubble up to the end after each pass.

